    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p1\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2004_p1\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: o = midpoint o b c\nGiven: m = on_circle m o b, on_line m a b\nGiven: n = on_circle n o b, on_line n a c\nGiven: r = angle_bisector r b a c, angle_bisector r m o n\nGiven: o1 = circle o1 b m r\nGiven: o2 = circle o2 c n r\nGiven: p = on_circle p o1 r, on_circle p o2 r\nProve: prove that points p, b, c are collinear\n\nGoal: coll p b c\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The construction forces two equal-power relations at the common point R, and because R lies on the angle bisector of both ∠BAC and ∠MON, the resulting chord directions imply that the second intersection P of the two circles must lie on the fixed line BC.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the midpoint condition to relate the circle through O and B to the line BC.\",\n    \"Exploit the fact that M lies on AB and N lies on AC, together with R on the two angle bisectors, to obtain equal angle relations involving B, C, M, N, and R.\",\n    \"Convert the cyclic conditions for O1 = (BMR) and O2 = (CNR) into equal power relations from P.\",\n    \"Show that the line through the two common points R and P is the radical axis of the two circles, and identify this axis with BC.\",\n    \"Conclude that P lies on BC.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points B, O, and C are collinear and OB = OC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since O is the midpoint of BC, it lies on line BC and is equidistant from B and C by definition of midpoint.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of midpoint\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points M and B lie on line AB, and points N and C lie on lines AB and AC respectively; moreover, MB = OB and NB = OB.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because M lies on the circle centered at O through B, we have OM = OB. Since M is also on line AB, the line AB intersects the circle centered at O through B at B and M. Similarly