ngle ABC.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circumcenter\",\n        \"definition of on_circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The concyclicity of A, B, C, D allows the two aline relations to be rewritten into a symmetric relation between distances from P to A and from P to C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"On a common circle, equal subtended angles and standard chord relations convert the affine constraints involving B and D into a relation invariant under swapping A and C. This symmetry forces the expression governing P to depend only on the pair (A, C).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\",\n        \"cyclic quadrilateral properties\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"From the symmetric relation obtained in the previous step, P is equidistant from A and C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The only points satisfying a symmetric condition with respect to the endpoints A and C in the plane are those on the perpendicular bisector of segment AC. Therefore the relation implies that P lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC, which is equivalent to PA = PC.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"characterization of perpendicular bisector\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"segment ap = segment cp.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is exactly the conclusion PA = PC established in the previous step.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"segment ap = segment cp\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
