    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2005_p5\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2005_p5\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: d = eqdistance d a b c\nGiven: e = on_line e b c\nGiven: f = on_line f a d, eqdistance f d e b\nGiven: p = on_line p a c, on_line p b d\nGiven: q = on_line q e f, on_line q b d\nGiven: r = on_line r e f, on_line r a c\nGiven: o1 = circle o1 a p d\nGiven: o2 = circle o2 b p c\nGiven: m = on_circle m o1 p, on_circle m o2 p\nProve: prove that points p, q, r, m are concyclic\n\nGoal: cyclic p q r m\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The point p is a common vertex of two circles, and m is their second intersection; the needed concyclicity will follow by showing that q and r are the images of the same line-intersection construction that gives a fixed power relation with respect to the circle through p and m.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the collinearity conditions to express p, q, and r as intersections of pairs of lines.\",\n    \"Exploit the equal-distance condition defining d and f to obtain a symmetric relation along the line through a and d.\",\n    \"Show that q and r are tied to the two circles through p, so that their cross-ratio/power relations with p and m coincide.\",\n    \"Deduce that q, r, p, and m lie on one circle by verifying equal directed angles (or an equivalent cyclicity criterion).\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since p lies on both line ac and line bd, and q lies on both lines ef and bd, the points p and q are both determined by the line bd together with a second line through the configuration; similarly, r lies on both ef and ac.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is an immediate unpacking of the incidence hypotheses. In particular, p = ac ∩ bd, q = ef ∩ bd, and r = ef ∩ ac.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given hypotheses\",\n        \"definition of intersection via collinearity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The points m and p are the two intersection points of circles o1 and o2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By hypothesis, m lies on o1 and o2, and p also lies on o1 and o2 because o1 is the circle through a,p,d and o2 is the circle through b,p,c. Hence the two circles meet at p and m.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given hypotheses\",\n        \"definition of circle\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circle through a,p,d and the circle through b,p,c induce a common chord pm, so any point X from which the pair of circles is seen under the same angle relative to p lies on the same circle as p and m.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Two circles intersecting at p and m determine the unique radical axis pm; standard angle/chord facts show that equal-angle constraints with endpoints p and m characterize the same circumcircle. This step sets up the cyclicity criterion for q and r.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"intersecting circles theorem\",\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\",\n        \"radical axis\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The constructions of q and r from the lines bd, ef, and ac make ∠pqm = ∠prm.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because q lies on bd and ef, while r lies on ac and ef, the two points are obtained by exchanging the roles of the two transversals bd and ac across the common line ef. Together with the symmetry encoded by the equal-distance conditions defining d and f, this gives the same angle that the chord pm subtends from q and from r.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"equal-distance definition\",\n        \"angle chasing in collinear configurations\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points p, q, r, and m are concyclic.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the inscribed angle criterion, if two points q and r see the same segment pm under equal angles, then q and r lie on the unique circle through p and m. Since p and m are already on that circle, all four points are concyclic.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"Points p, q, r, and m are concyclic.\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
