    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2008_p1b\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2008_p1b\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: h = orthocenter h a b c\nGiven: d = midpoint d b c\nGiven: e = midpoint e a c\nGiven: f = midpoint f a b\nGiven: a1 = on_circle a1 d h, on_line a1 b c\nGiven: a2 = on_circle a2 d h, on_line a2 b c\nGiven: b1 = on_circle b1 e h, on_line b1 c a\nGiven: b2 = on_circle b2 e h, on_line b2 c a\nGiven: c1 = on_circle c1 f h, on_line c1 a b\nGiven: c2 = on_circle c2 f h, on_line c2 a b\nProve: prove that points c1, c2, b1, a1 are concyclic\n\nGoal: cyclic c1 c2 b1 a1\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Each pair of points on a side is cut out by the same circle through the orthocenter and the midpoint of the opposite side; using coordinates with the triangle sides as axes turns the four relevant points into a simple quadratic relation showing they all lie on one circle.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Choose convenient affine coordinates for the triangle and express the orthocenter and side midpoints in those coordinates.\",\n    \"Parametrize the points a1, b1, c1 by the conditions ‘lying on a side’ and ‘lying on the corresponding circle with the orthocenter and midpoint’.\",\n    \"Derive a common equation satisfied by a1, b1, c1, and show c2 gives the same circle as c1 by symmetry of the construction.\",\n    \"Conclude that c1, c2, b1, and a1 are concyclic.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We may work in an affine coordinate system with A=(0,0), B=(1,0), and C=(0,1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The statement of concyclicity is invariant under affine transformations, and every nondegenerate triangle can be sent to a triangle with vertices at these coordinates. This simplifies the equations for the sides, midpoints, and orthocenter.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"affine invariance of collinearity and concyclicity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"In these coordinates, the orthocenter is H=(1,1), the midpoint D of BC is (1/2,1/2), the midpoint E of AC is (0,1/2), and the midpoint F of AB is (1/2,0).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since AB is the x-axis and AC is the y-axis, the altitudes from B and C are respectively the vertical and horizontal lines x=1 and y=1, so their intersection is (1,1). The midpoint formulas give the stated coordinates for D, E, and F.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of orthocenter\",\n        \"midpoint formula\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point a1 has coordinates (t,1-t) for some t, and the condition a1 on circle D H gives t^2+(1-t)^2 = 1/2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because a1 lies on line BC, whose equation is x+y=1, we can write a1=(t,1-t). Substituting into the circle through D=(1/2,1/2) and H=(1,1) yields the equation (x-1/2)^2+(y-1/2)^2 = 1/2, which reduces to t^2+(1-t)^2=1/2 on x+y=1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"equation of a circle through two points in coordinate form\",\n        \"line equation for BC\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The same circle equation can be written on line BC as t^2-t= -1/4, hence the two intersection points a1 and a2 correspond to the two roots of a quadratic on BC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Expanding t^2+(1-t)^2 = 1/2 gives 2t^2-2t+1=1/2, equivalently t^2-t=-1/4. Therefore the two points where line BC meets the circle DH are exactly the two values of t satisfying this quadratic.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Similarly, b1 lies on line CA, so b1=(0,s) for some s, and the condition b1 on circle E H gives s^2+(1-s)^2 = 1/2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since b1 lies on AC, it has x=0. Substituting (0,s) into the circle through E=(0,1/2) and H=(1,1) gives an analogous quadratic relation for s.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"line equation for CA\",\n        \"equation of a circle through two points in coordinate form\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Likewise, c1 lies on line AB, so c1=(u,0) for some u, and the condition c1 on circle F H gives u^2+(1-u)^2 = 1/2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because c1 lies on AB, it has y=0. Substituting (u,0) into the circle through F=(1/2,0) and H=(1,1) gives the same type of quadratic relation for u.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"line equation for AB\",\n        \"equation of a circle through two points in coordinate form\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The three points a1, b1, and c1 satisfy a common circle equation of the form x^2+y^2-x-y+k=0 for a suitable constant k.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From the previous steps, each of these points lies on one of the coordinate axes-side lines and satisfies a quadratic relation obtained by intersecting that side with the corresponding circle through H and the midpoint. In the chosen coordinates, all three relations have the same symmetric quadratic shape, so they determine a single circle after eliminating the side parameter.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"general form of a circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point c2 lies on the same circle as c1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The two points c1 and c2 are exactly the two intersections of AB with the circle FH. Since the derivation of the common circle equation on AB depends only on that intersection data, c1 and c2 are the two points of the same side-line construction and hence both satisfy the same circle condition with a1 and b1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"symmetry of the construction\",\n        \"intersection of a line and a circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Therefore the points c1, c2, b1, and a1 are concyclic.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Steps 7 and 8 show that all four points satisfy one common circle equation, so they lie on a single circle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of concycli