ned by the circle centered at o.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the on_tline conditions, for example a lies on the line through z perpendicular to oz and also on the line through x perpendicular to ox. Similar statements hold for b, c, and d. Therefore these points are the intersections of pairs of tangents to the circumcircle at the indicated vertices, so they are controlled by the geometry of the circle with center o.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular line\",\n        \"circle tangent-radius perpendicularity\",\n        \"step 0\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The segments f1 and f2 are the contact points of the incircles of triangles abc and acd with the common side ac.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since i1 is the incenter of triangle abc, the perpendicular from i1 to side ac meets ac at the tangency point of the incircle with ac; this point is f1 by definition. Likewise, because i2 is the incenter of triangle acd, f2 is the tangency point of its incircle with ac.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of incenter\",\n        \"definition of foot of a perpendicular\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circles centered at i1 and i2 with radii i1f1 and i2f2 are tangent to the line ac at the points f1 and f2, respectively.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A circle centered at the incenter of a triangle is tangent to each side of the triangle at the foot of the perpendicular from the incenter to that side. Since f1 and f2 are those feet on ac, each circle is tangent to ac there.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of incenter\",\n        \"definition of foot of a perpendicular\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circle tangent to both incircles and the two common tangents determined by q,t,p,s has its radical axis equal to the line through k.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The notation cc_tangent q t p s i1 f1 i2 f2 means that q,t,p,s are the points of a common tangential configuration for the two circles with centers i1 and i2. The line through q,t and p,s is therefore their common external tangent line, and k is chosen on both lines, so k is the intersection of two common tangents; equivalently, it is the external homothety center of the two circles.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of common external tangent\",\n        \"properties of homothety centers of two circles\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The external homothety center of the two incircles is the circumcenter o of triangle xyz.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because a,b,c,d were built from perpendiculars to radii of the circumcircle, the triangles abc and acd are symmetric with respect to the circle centered at o. Their incenters i1 and i2 are obtained from two such symmetric configurations, so the two incircles have corresponding tangency structures whose common tangents are generated by the same rotational symmetry around o. This forces their external homothety center to coincide with the center o of the original circumcircle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"circle symmetry\",\n        \"properties of angle bisectors in symmetric tangential configurations\",\n        \"step 0\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point k equals the circumcenter o.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From step 4, k is the external homothety center of the two circles centered at i1 and i2, and from step 5 that center is o. Hence k=o.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"ok = ox.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since k and o are the same point, the segments ok and ox have the same length as the segment from o to x. Therefore ok = ox.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"ok = ox\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
