pendicular to the radius drawn to the tangency point.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of tangent line\",\n        \"radius-tangent perpendicularity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because w is the circle through M, L, K, the radius at M is perpendicular to the line through the center of w and M, and the tangent relation from step 2 fixes the direction of MQ relative to the triangle M L K.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The circle w is determined by the triangle M, L, K, so its center is the circumcenter of triangle MLK. The tangent at M is perpendicular to the radius through M, which gives a rigid geometric constraint on MQ.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"circumcircle definition\",\n        \"radius-tangent perpendicularity\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since b = mirror b p k, point K is the midpoint of segment PB and points P, K, B are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"As in step 1, point reflection across K sends P to B. Thus K is the midpoint of PB and P, K, B lie on one line.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of point reflection/mirror image\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since c = mirror c q l, point L is the midpoint of segment QC and points Q, L, C are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Again by the definition of point reflection, L is the center of symmetry between Q and C, so L is the midpoint of QC and Q, L, C are collinear.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of point reflection/mirror image\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The conditions on_line a b q and on_line a c p imply that A is the intersection of lines BQ and CP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The first condition says A lies on line BQ, and the second says A lies on line CP. Therefore A is their intersection point.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of point lying on a line\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because O is the circle through