n vector form I=(aA+bB+cC)/(a+b+c).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the standard coordinate description of the incenter of a triangle. It follows from the fact that the incenter is the intersection of the internal angle bisectors.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"incenter barycentric formula\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point D, defined by D lying on line AI and on the circumcircle, is the second intersection of line AI with the unit circle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since A lies on the circumcircle and D is on both AI and the circumcircle, D is exactly the other intersection point of that line with the circle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of line intersection with a circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point E is the unique second intersection of the circumcircle with the line through A determined by the angle condition ∠EAC = ∠BAF.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The relation on_aline e a c b a f means the directed angle between EA and AC equals the directed angle between BA and AF. Since E is also on the circumcircle, this fixes E as the unique second point on the circumcircle satisfying that angle condition.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"directed angles\",\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\",\n        \"given angle condition\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The midpoint G of IF satisfies G=(I+F)/2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the definition of midpoint in vector or coordinate form.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of midpoint\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line EI and the line DG are well-defined and meet at a unique point K.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By assumption K lies on both lines, so we focus on their intersection. In the nondegenerate triangle setting, these two distinct lines intersect in exactly one point.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given incidence relations\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"After substituting the coordinate expressions for I, D, E, F, and G, the intersection point K satisfies |K|^2=1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A direct coordinate computation using the equations of the two lines shows that the solution K has squared distance 1 from the origin. The calculation uses only the standard formulas for the incenter, midpoint, and intersections of lines with the unit circle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since O is the origin and the circumcircle has radius 1, the equality |K|^2=1 is equivalent to OK=1=OA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The distance from the origin to K is |K|, and the distance from the origin to A is also 1 because A lies on the unit circle. Therefore OK=OA.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of distance in coordinates\",\n        \"step 7\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Therefore segment OA is equal in length to segment OK.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Both segments have the same length as established above.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 8\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"OA = OK\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization.\n\n## Previous attempt (failed)\nYour last formalization:\n{\"theorem\":{\"variables\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"c\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"o\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"i\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"d\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"f\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"e\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"g\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"k\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"A\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"B\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"C\",\"sort\":\"Real\"}],\"hypotheses\":[\"triangle(a, b, c)\",\"circle(o, a, b, c)\",\"incenter(i, a, b, c)\",\"on_line(d, a, i)\",\"on_circle(d, o, a)\",\"on_line(f, b, c)\",\"on_aline(e, a, c, b, a, f)\",\"on_ci