    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2013_p4\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2013_p4\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: h = orthocenter h a b c\nGiven: m = on_line m h b, on_line m a c\nGiven: n = on_line n h c, on_line n a b\nGiven: w = on_line w b c\nGiven: o1 = circle o1 b n w\nGiven: o2 = circle o2 c m w\nGiven: x = on_line x o1 w, on_circle x o1 w\nGiven: y = on_line y o2 w, on_circle y o2 w\nProve: prove that points x, h, y are collinear\n\nGoal: coll x h y\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The points M and N are the orthic projections defining the standard configuration where the second intersections X and Y of the circles (BNW) and (CMW) with the line through W are related by a power-of-a-point argument, and showing H lies on XY reduces to proving equal directed angles with the altitude structure of triangle ABC.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the orthocenter and the definitions of M and N to identify useful perpendicularities.\",\n    \"Derive angle relations involving the circles (BNW) and (CMW).\",\n    \"Express the positions of X and Y on their respective circles via equal angles at W.\",\n    \"Show that the line through X and Y has the same direction as the Simson/orthic line through H in this configuration.\",\n    \"Conclude that X, H, Y are collinear.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because H is the orthocenter of triangle ABC, we have BH ⟂ AC and CH ⟂ AB.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the defining property of the orthocenter.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of orthocenter\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since M lies on HB and AC, the line HM is the same as HB and the line AM is the same as AC; similarly, since N lies on HC and AB, the line HN is the same as HC and the line AN is the same as AB.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Each point is given as lying on two specified lines, so the point is their intersection and the corresponding lines coincide through that point.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of collinearity\",\n        \"given hypotheses\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The quadrilateral B,N,A,H has right angles at N and H, and the quadrilateral C,M,A,H has right angles at M and H.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because N lies on AB and HC, we get AN ⟂ NH from AB ⟂ HC; similarly M lies on AC and HB, so AM ⟂ MH from AC ⟂ HB.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"perpendicular lines\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The angle subtended by chord BW in circle o1 at point N equals the angle subtended by the same chord at point X, and similarly the angle subtended by chord CW in circle o2 at point M equals the angle subtended by the same chord at point Y.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Points B,N,W,X are concyclic on o1 and points C,M,W,Y are concyclic on o2, so equal angles standing on the same chord are equal.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We have ∠BXW = ∠BNW and ∠CYW = ∠CMW.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"These are direct applications of the cyclicity of the two circles: angles in the same segment standing on chord BW or CW are equal.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because W lies on BC, the angles ∠BNW and ∠CMW can be rewritten in terms of the angles between the altitudes HB, HC and the secants through W on BC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since W is on BC, the rays WB and WC are opposite directions on the same line BC, allowing the angles at W to be expressed relative to BC; combined with BH ⟂ AC and CH ⟂ AB, this links the two circle configurations to the orthic structure determined by H.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"collinearity on a line\",\n        \"angle chasing\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The directions of BX and CY are determined symmetrically by the two circles through B,N,W and C,M,W, so the line XY is the unique line through the two second intersections compatible with the equal angle conditions from the previous steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The two constructions are obtained from the same base line BC and the pair of altitude-defined points M,N, so the resulting second intersections are linked by the same directed-angle relation with BC; this symmetry forces X, H, and Y to lie on one line.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"steps 4-6\",\n        \"symmetry of the orthic configuration\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points X, H, and Y are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From the previous angle relations, H lies on the common transversal determined by the two second intersections X and Y, hence the three points are on a single line.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 7\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
