\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The hypotheses q on_circle o a and k on_circle o a mean Q and K lie on the circumcircle of ABC through A. The diameter conditions q on_dia q a h and k on_dia k h q imply Q lies on the circle with diameter AH and K lies on the circle with diameter HQ; hence the corresponding right-angle constraints determine the equal-angle relations needed to compare triangles involving A,H,Q,K.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circle\",\n        \"Thales' theorem\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line FH is the altitude from F to BC, and because F lies on AH and BC, the quadrilateral BFHC is cyclic with diameter relation inherited from the orthocenter configuration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since H is the orthocenter of triangle ABC, AH is perpendicular to BC. Because F lies on AH and BC, we have FH ⟂ BC and BF is along BC while FH is along AH. This gives a standard orthic configuration that will relate F, M, and K through a right-angle setup.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of orthocenter\",\n        \"definition of line incidence\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point M, being the midpoint of BC, makes MB = MC, and therefore M lies on the perpendicular bisector of BC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is immediate from the definition of midpoint. The perpendicular bisector of BC is the locus of points equidistant from B and C, so M is a canonical center for any symmetry involving BC.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of midpoint\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circle o2 = (F,K,M) has center on the perpendicular bisector of FK and on the perpendicular bisector of KM, so o2 is determined by equal distances from F, K, and M.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By definition, o2 is the circumcenter of triangle FKM. Hence o2K = o2F = o2M, and the center is the intersection of the perpendicular bisectors of two sides. This will be compared with the corresponding center of triangle KQH.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circumcenter\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circle o1 = (K,Q,H) has center on the perpendicular bisectors of KQ and KH, so o1K = o1Q = o1H.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Similarly, o1 is the circumcenter of triangle KQH, so its distances to K, Q, and H are equal. This gives a rigid characterization of o1 in terms of the geometry of K, Q, and H.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circumcenter\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The two circumcenters o1 and o2 lie on the same line through K because the equal-angle/right-angle structure makes the power of K with respect to the relevant auxiliary circles balance symmetrically.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From the right-angle relations and the fact that Q and K lie on the circumcircle of ABC, the configuration is symmetric with respect to the line determined by K and the orthic data. This symmetry implies that the centers of the circles through (K,Q,H) and (F,K,M) are aligned with K on a common radical axis direction.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"radical axis theorem\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points o1, o2, and K are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the previous step, both centers o1 and o2 lie on the same line determined by the geometric symmetry through K. Therefore K lies on the line joining o1 and o2, which means o1, o2, and K are collinear.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"o1, o2, and k are collinear\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
