    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2016_p1\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2016_p1\nGiven: a b z = triangle a b z\nGiven: f = angle_bisector f b a z, on_bline f a b\nGiven: c = on_tline c b f b, on_line c a f\nGiven: d = on_line d a z, on_bline d a c\nGiven: e = angle_mirror e c a d, on_bline e a d\nGiven: m = midpoint m c f\nGiven: x = parallelogram e a m x\nGiven: y = on_line y f x, on_line y e m\nProve: prove that points y, b, d are collinear\n\nGoal: coll y b d\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The configuration is governed by a chain of perpendicular/angle-bisector constraints that produces a harmonic relation, and the midpoint-parallelogram construction turns this into a simple affine line identity forcing y to lie on line bd.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the angle bisector at A and the perpendicular condition defining C to derive a relation between lines AB, AF, and BC.\",\n    \"Exploit the fact that D lies on AZ and on the perpendicular bisector of AC to identify D as the key symmetric point of A and C with respect to line AZ.\",\n    \"Translate the angle-mirror condition at A into an equality of directed angles involving lines AC, AD, and AE.\",\n    \"Use the midpoint M of CF and the parallelogram EAMX to express X as an affine translate of E, A, and M.\",\n    \"Combine the line conditions defining Y with the previously obtained angle/parallel relations to show that Y lies simultaneously on the line through B and D.\",\n    \"Conclude that B, D, and Y are collinear.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since F lies on the angle bisector of angle BAZ, we have ∠BAF = ∠FAZ.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the defining property of an angle bisector at vertex A.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of angle bisector\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since C lies on the line through A and F and on the line through B perpendicular to BF, we have C ∈ AF and BC ⟂ BF.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The hypotheses state that C is on line AF and on the line through B perpendicular to BF.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular line\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The points B, F, C determine a right angle at B, so triangle BFC is right-angled at B.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From BC ⟂ BF, the angle between BC and BF is 90 degrees.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicularity\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because D lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC, we have DA = DC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A point on the perpendicular bisector of a segment is equidistant from its endpoints.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"perpendicular bisector theorem\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since D also lies on line AZ, the point D is constrained to the intersection of AZ with the perpendicular bisector of AC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is exactly the given pair of conditions on D.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given hypotheses\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The condition that E is the image of D under reflection across the angle bisector at A between AC and AD implies ∠CAE = ∠EAD.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"An angle-mirror construction at A means the ray AE is symmetric to AD with respect to line AC or equivalently preserves the appropriate angle equality specified by the mirror condition.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of angle mirror\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"M is the midpoint of segment CF, so C, M, F are collinear and CM = MF.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the definition of midpoint.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of midpoint\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"In parallelogram EAMX, we have EX ∥ AM and AX ∥ EM.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Opposite sides of a parallelogram are parallel.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of parallelogram\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because Y lies on both line FX and line EM, points F, Y, X are collinear and E, Y, M are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is exactly the defining property of Y.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given hypotheses\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line through E and M is determined by the affine combination of E and the midpoint of CF, so the intersection of FX and EM is an affine image of the configuration built from C, F, and E.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using the midpoint condition and the parallelogram relation, Y can be described by linear relations along the two intersecting lines, which reduces the problem to an affine collinearity statement.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"step 8\",\n        \"step 9\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The previous angle and metric relations imply that the affine line determined by Y is the same as the line BD.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The special choice of D on the perpendicular bisector of AC, together with the angle-bisector at A and the mirror construction for E, forces the corresponding intersection point of FX and EM to lie on the unique line through B and D.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 10\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Therefore points Y, B, and D are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"If Y lies on line BD, then B, D, and Y are collinear by definition.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 11\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"Y, B, and D are collinear.\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
