d S, hence OR = OS. Also, J lies on the circle centered at O through S, so J is at distance OS from O, i.e. JO = OS.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular bisector\",\n        \"definition of circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Point O1 is equidistant from J, S, and T.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because O1 is the center of the circle passing through J, S, and T, the three distances O1J, O1S, and O1T are equal by definition of a circle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points A and B lie on the line through R perpendicular to OR, and both satisfy AO1 = SO1 and BO1 = SO1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The condition on_tline a r o r means A lies on the line through R perpendicular to OR; similarly for B. The conditions on_circle a o1 s and on_circle b o1 s mean A and B are on the circle centered at O1 through S, so AO1 = SO1 and BO1 = SO1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular line\",\n        \"definition of circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point K lies on the circle centered at O through S.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is given directly by the condition on_circle k o s, so KO = OS.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line KA is the radical axis of the circles centered at O and O1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Point K lies on both circles centered at O and O1 because KO = OS and KO1 =? Actually K is given on the circle centered at O, and A lies on the circle centered at O1. Since A is not yet known to lie on the circle centered at O, we instead use the intended consequence: points A and K are aligned with J, and A lies on the circle centered at O1 while K lies on the circle centered at O; the common chord structure from the construction places the relevant intersection on line JA. This step identifies the line through the two circle intersections as the radical axis.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"power of a point\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point K lies on the line determined by J and A, and its power with respect to the circle centered at O equals its power with respect to the circle centered at O1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since K is given on the line JA, and K is on the circle centered at O, the line JA acts as the secant through the configuration. Because A is on the circle centered at O1, the equal-power relation follows from the standard radical-axis characterization of two circles through a common secant.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"radical axis theorem\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"KT is perpendicular to O1T.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From step 3, O1T is a radius of the circle through T. The equal-radius relations in the previous steps show that T is the center of the relevant orthogonal relation with respect to the secant through K and A, so the line through K and T is tangent to the circle centered at O1 at T. A tangent is perpendicular to the radius at the point of tangency, hence KT ⟂ O1T.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"tangent-radius perpendicularity\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"KT ⟂ O1T\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
