ties.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular bisector\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The equalities FB = FD and GC = GE determine F and G as the second intersections of the circumcircle (ABC) with circles centered at B and C of radii BD and CE, respectively.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because F and G are also on the circumcircle through A,B,C, each point is characterized as lying on two circles: the circumcircle and the circle forced by the perpendicular-bisector equality. This reformulation will allow chord/angle comparisons on the circumcircle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The angle between line DF and line AB equals the angle between line DE and line AC, and the corresponding angle between line FG and line DE is controlled by the same circular chord data.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since D lies on AB and E lies on AC, any angle involving D or E with AB or AC can be rewritten in terms of the triangles formed with the cyclic points A,B,C,F,G. The key consequence is that the directions of DF and EG are encoded by equal-chord relations on the common circumcircle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The directed angle from line DE to line FG is zero.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using the cyclic configuration and the equal-distance conditions FB = FD and GC = GE, one obtains the same angle relation for the segment through D to F as for the segment through E to G, so the two lines have the same direction. Therefore DE and FG are parallel.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"inscribed angle theorem\",\n        \"congruence from equal chords\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"line DE ∥ line FG.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is exactly the conclusion of the previous step.\",\n   