, q q1) = ∠(b c, c a), so the line qq1 is determined by the same reference angle ∠BCA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Again, the equal-angle notation identifies the directed angle between the first two lines with that between the second two lines. Since q1 lies on the line through q and a1, the relevant line through q is qq1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of eqangle3\",\n        \"definition of incidence\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because q lies on the line through b and b1 and is also on the line through p parallel to ab, the direction of q a1 is the same as the direction of a b, while the direction of p b1 is determined by the cevian p a1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The condition q = on_pline p a b means pq is parallel to ab. Since a1 lies on bc, the line qa1 forms angles with q that can be compared to angles at B and C using the parallelism pq ∥ ab and the collinearity of a1, b, c. Similarly, p1 lies on pb1, so p1 is controlled by the cevian through b1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of parallel lines\",\n        \"definition of incidence\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The directed angle ∠(p p1, p q1) equals the directed angle ∠(a c, c b) + ∠(b c, c a), and the same total angle appears for ∠(q q1, q p1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From the previous steps, the direction of pp1 is tied to the angle at C in triangle ABC, while qq1 is tied to the complementary angle at C. Since p q is parallel to a b, the angles formed with the transversal lines through a1 and b1 transfer the same reference angles to the quadrilateral p q p1 q1. Adding the two equal-angle contributions gives the same total turning for both relevant sides.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"angle addition\",\n        \"parallel line angle properties\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"∠p p1 q1 = ∠p q1 q.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The angle ∠p p1 q1 is the angle between pp1 and p1q1, and by the construction of p1 and q1 this angle is equal to the angle determined by the same reference directions as ∠p q1 q. The previous step shows that both angles are obtained from the same angle-chasing data in triangle ABC, hence they are equal.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"definition of cyclic quadrilateral via equal angles\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Points p, q, p1, q1 are concyclic.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A quadrilateral is cyclic if and only if a pair of opposite angles are equal. Since ∠p p1 q1 = ∠p q1 q, the four points lie on one circle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"criterion for cyclic quadrilateral\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization.\n\n## Previous attempt (failed)\nYour last formalization:\n{\"theorem\":{\"variables\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"c\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"a1\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"b1\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"p\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"q\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"p1\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"q1\",\"sort\":\"Real\"}],\"hypotheses\":[\"triangle(a, b, c)\",\"on_line(a1, b, c)\",\"on_line(b1, a, c)\",\"on_line(p, a, a1)\",\"And(on_line(q, b, b1), on_pline(p, a, b))\",\"And(on_line(p1, p, b1), eqangle3(p, c, a, b, c))\",\"And(on_line(q1, q, a1), eqangle3(c, q, b, c, a))\"],\"goal\":\"cyclic(p, q, p1, q1)\"},\"functions\":[],\"lemmas\":[{\"name\":\"eqangle3_def\",\"english\":\"The three-point equal-angle predicate implies equality of the directed angles of the two line pairs it relates.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"x1\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"x2\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"x3\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"y1\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"y2\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"y3\",\"sort\":\"Real\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(eqangle3(x1, x2, x3, y1, y2,