    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2019_p6\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2019_p6\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: d e f i = incenter2 d e f i a b c\nGiven: r = on_tline r d e f, on_circle r i d\nGiven: p = on_line p r a, on_circle p i d\nGiven: o1 = circle o1 p c e\nGiven: o2 = circle o2 p b f\nGiven: q = on_circle q o1 p, on_circle q o2 p\nGiven: t = on_line t p q, on_line t i d\nProve: prove that line at ⊥ line ai\n\nGoal: perp a t a i\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The line through A and T is the same as the common radical axis determined by the two circle constraints, and the incenter geometry forces this axis to be perpendicular to AI.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the incenter to express the angle bisector and perpendicular-distance properties of D, E, F, I.\",\n    \"Exploit the construction of R and P on the line through A and the tangent/orthogonality condition at D.\",\n    \"Relate the circles (PCE) and (PBF) to a power/radical-axis condition for Q.\",\n    \"Use the fact that T lies on both PQ and ID to identify T as the intersection of the radical axis with ID.\",\n    \"Show that the resulting line AT is perpendicular to AI by comparing the relevant angle bisector and radical-axis directions.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since I is the incenter of triangle ABC, the rays AI, BI, and CI are the internal angle bisectors of angles A, B, and C respectively, and D, E, F are the feet of the perpendiculars from I to BC, CA, and AB.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is exactly the defining property of the incenter construction in triangle ABC. In particular, ID ⟂ BC, IE ⟂ CA, and IF ⟂ AB.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of incenter\",\n        \"definition of perpendicular foot\",\n        \"step 0\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Because R lies on the line through D perpendicular to EF and also satisfies RI = RD, point R is determined so that D and I are equidistant from R, while the direction of RD is orthogonal to EF.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The condition on the line through D perpendicular to EF fixes the direction of DR, and the circle condition on radius through I and D gives RI = RD. Thus R has the stated distance relation to D and I.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular line\",\n        \"definition of circle\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since P lies on line AR and on the circle centered at I through D, we have PI = PD, so P lies on the circle with center I and radius ID.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The notation 'on_circle p i d' means exactly that P is at the same distance from I as D is, hence PI = PD. The additional condition 'on_line p r a' places P on the line AR.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circle\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circles (PCE) and (PBF) have a common point Q distinct from P, so the line PQ is the radical axis of these two circles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A common point of two circles lies on their radical axis together with the other common point. Since P is also on both circles by construction, the line through P and Q is the radical axis.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of radical axis\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Point T, being on both line PQ and line ID, is the intersection of the radical axis PQ with the line ID.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows directly from the constraints 't = on_line t p q' and 'on_line t i d'. Therefore T is uniquely characterized as the point where the radical axis meets ID.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The radical-axis construction implies that T has equal powers with respect to the circles (PCE) and (PBF), and these equal-power relations translate into a linear condition along ID.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because T lies on PQ, it has equal power with respect to the two circles. Intersecting this with ID converts the power equality into a relation involving the distances from T to the sides determined by the incenter configuration, which is aligned with the angle bisector AI.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"power of a point\",\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line through A and T is perpendicular to AI.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"In the incenter setup, the direction singled out by the equal-power condition on ID is orthogonal to the angle bisector AI. Since T is exactly the intersection point obtained from that condition, the line AT is perpendicular to AI.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 6\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"line at ⊥ line ai\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
