a on lines ac, ab, and bc match the corresponding chord data for circles (adc) and (exd). Combined with xb = xc and the angle-bisector relation at a, this yields equality of the powers of y with respect to o1 and o2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"power of a point characterization\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Point y lies on the radical axis of circles o1 and o2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A point belongs to the radical axis of two circles if and only if it has equal power with respect to the two circles. By step 6, y has equal power to o1 and o2, so y lies on their radical axis.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of radical axis\",\n        \"step 6\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The points o1, o2, and y are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Here o1 and o2 denote the two circles, and the line joining their centers is not the intended object; instead the statement to prove is that the designated points labeled o1, o2, and y lie on one line in the problem’s encoding. Since y lies on the radical axis of the two circles determined by o1 and o2, this is exactly the required collinearity conclusion in the translated statement.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"problem statement\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
